{[show NESW]
[ROLE leader][STAGE pre-lead]
Lead the \HK. It is the top of your sequence and your longest suit — the standard notrump attack, hoping to set up your long hearts before declarer gathers his tricks.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE auction-end]
You are in 3\N with two finesses to work with, a spade finesse and a club finesse. West's \HK warns you that hearts is his suit, so he is the danger hand. Here is the discipline of the deal: both of your finesses, if they lose, lose to EAST — and East is the safe hand. So you can take them both without fear. Duck the opening heart to cut the defenders' link, then help yourself to both chances.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE post-lead]
West's \HK marks the danger: a long heart suit sitting over your single stopper. Duck the first heart — East began with only two, so one hold-up leaves him with none — then win the second. Now run the spade finesse toward your \SA\SQ\SJ, and if you should need it, the club finesse as well. Both lose only to East, who has no heart left to lead, so combining your two chances costs you nothing. The spade king is onside; home you come.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE post-play]
The skill here was not choosing between the finesses — it was noticing that both were safe, so you never had to choose. Read which defender is dangerous, steer your losers to the other one, and you can take every chance the hand offers.}
