{[show NESW]
[ROLE leader][STAGE pre-lead]
Lead the \HK, top of your sequence in your longest suit, and drive out declarer's stopper while you still hold the length.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE auction-end]
Your two extra chances are a spade finesse for the queen and a club finesse for the queen — and, once more, both lose to East, the safe hand. West's \HK brands hearts as the danger, so plan a hold-up before you touch the finesses: with a loss going only to harmless East, taking both your chances is completely safe.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE post-lead]
Hold up your \HA — East started with three hearts, so duck the first two rounds and win the third, and East is stripped bare. Now take the spade finesse toward your \SA\SK\SJ and, if it is not enough, the club finesse toward dummy's \CA\CK\C9. Either loss goes to East, who can no longer reach West's winners. The spade queen sits right; nine tricks.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE post-play]
Both finesses lost, if they lost at all, to the hand that could do no damage. That is what let you combine your chances instead of gambling on one: find the safe hand first, and finesse into it.}
