[ROLE leader][STAGE pre-lead]
Lead the \HK from your six-card suit — top of the sequence. With so many hearts, setting them up is your side's best hope.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE auction-end]
West leads from what looks like a six-card heart suit, and you hold it just once, so the hold-up is critical. Your two chances are a spade finesse and a club finesse — and both, if they lose, lose to East, who began with only a doubleton heart. Duck one round to leave East with none, and then both finesses are perfectly safe.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE post-lead]
Hold up your \HA on the first round; East, with two hearts, is void after the second. Now the danger is dead: West has all the long hearts but no way to reach them, because your spade and club finesses both lose to the heartless East. Take them both — the spade king is onside — and claim ten tricks.

[ROLE declarer][STAGE post-play]
West's six-card suit never scored a single trick, because you ducked at the right moment and kept the dangerous hand off lead for the rest of the deal. A long suit is only as good as the entries to cash it — deny them, and even your finesses become risk-free.}
